04666nam a22005415i 9780822385516DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223855167 a10.1515/97808223855162doi  a(DE-B1597)552134  a(OCoLC)1229161541  a(OCoLC)1170626854  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1993.5.I846bF57 2004 7aPER0040002bisacsh04a791.43/09551 aFischer, Michael M. J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMute Dreams, Blind Owls, and Dispersed Knowledges :bPersian Poesis in the Transnational Circuitry /cMichael M. J. Fischer. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (486 p.) :b58 illustrations, 10 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tBy Way of Acknowledgments: Divided Selves and Doubled Genealogies -- tPrelude: After Epic, Writing, Painting, and Film -- tI. Speaking After Zarathustra: Ritual, Epic, and Philosophical Forms of Reason -- tPrologue -- t1. Yasna: Performative Ritual, Narrative Mnemonic -- t2. Shahnameh: Parable Logic -- tCoda: Illuminationism: Philosophical Allegory -- tII. Seeing After Film: Textual and Cinematic Forms of Ethical Reason -- t3. Awaiting the Revolution: Surrealism Persian Style -- t4. Filmic Judgment and Cultural Critique: The Work of Art, Ethics, and Religion in Postrevolution Iranian Cinema -- t5. War Again: Qandahar, 911- Figure and Discourse in Iranian Cinematic Writing -- tCoda: Balancing Acts (After 9/11) -- tEpilogue: Beyond ''Mobile Armies of Metaphors'': Scheherezade Films the Games -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past decade Iranian films have received enormous international attention, garnering both critical praise and popular success. Combining his extensive ethnographic experience in Iran and his broad command of critical theory, Michael M. J. Fischer argues that the widespread appeal of Iranian cinema is based in a poetics that speaks not only to Iran's domestic cultural politics but also to the more general ethical dilemmas of a world simultaneously torn apart and pushed together. Approaching film as a tool for anthropological analysis, he illuminates how Iranian filmmakers have incorporated and remade the rich traditions of oral, literary, and visual media in Persian culture.Fischer reveals how the distinctive expressive idiom emerging in contemporary Iranian film reworks Persian imagery that has itself been in dialogue with other cultures since the time of Zoroaster and ancient Greece. He examines a range of narrative influences on this expressive idiom and imagery, including Zoroastrian ritual as it is practiced in Iran, North America, and India; the mythic stories, moral lessons, and historical figures written about in Iran's national epic, the Shahnameh; the dreamlike allegorical world of Persian surrealism exemplified in Sadeq Hedayat's 1939 novella The Blind Owl; and the politically charged films of the 1960s and 1970s. Fischer contends that by combining Persian traditions with cosmopolitan influences, contemporary Iranian filmmakers-many of whom studied in Europe and America-provide audiences around the world with new modes of accessing ethical and political experiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aMotion pictureszIranxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822385516zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822385516423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822385516.jpg  